Elon Musk is forced to step down as chairman of Tesla’s board of directors
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their fraud case.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the channel, within the framework of the agreements reached, Musk will have to leave the post of chairman of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Mask to retain the post of Tesla CEO.
The founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $20 million.
A similar amount will be demanded from Tesla.
At the same time, the money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur who is on the list of the 50 richest people on the planet according to Forbes magazine.
He is the CEO of SpaceX, the neurotechnology company Neuralink, and the developer of Tesla’s electric cars, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has previously sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk over his announcement on Twitter about a possible takeover of the company.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy back all shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The share price of $420 was set “because of the importance of this number in the culture of marijuana,” Bloomberg reported earlier, citing co-director of the commission’s security department, Stephen Pekin.
Elon Musk later declined his plans to buy back the shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said he considers the allegations of fraud unfounded and added that he was very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
“Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I did not violate it in any way,” the businessman said in an interview with CNBC.
In August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a class action lawsuit against Musk, complaining of financial losses.
The plaintiffs claimed that the posts of the businessman brought them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders said that the tweets of the businessman misled, which is why Tesla stock sellers were forced to buy papers at artificially overpriced prices to cover their positions.
Other plaintiffs also noted that the careless statements of Elon Musk led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Elon Musk also accused the head of research company Citron Research of stock market manipulation.
Meanwhile, if Musk had not been able to settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he would have been threatened with removal from management of the company and even prison.
This was reported by former chairman of the commission, Harvey Pitt, on CNBC.
Musk is a “good guy who can’t manage a car company.”
