ADG became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant "Alternative for Germany" is breaking another record of popularity, and Angela Merkel's ratings are falling.
It seems that Germans are seriously tired of Angela Merkel’s immigration policy, which has made the country a coveted destination for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
This is most evident in recent social surveys, according to which the anti-immigrant party "Alternative for Germany" is becoming increasingly popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the AdG broke another record, rising to the second place in the ranking of popular sympathies.
The right-wing conservatives with 17 percent of the popularity managed to bypass the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The gap of one percentage point can be attributed to a statistical error, but it cannot be ignored the fact that the ADG created in 2013 from a small group of eurosceptic economists managed to turn into a serious political force.
Leadership in general continues to hold the ruling HSS/CDS bloc, which has about 30 per cent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points – back in April, Angela Merkel’s support was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also declining.
Today, 48% of Germans support Angela Merkel, which is 7% lower than last year.
The Social Democrats were followed by the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
Evolution of "Alternatives"
The Alternative for Germany party was created in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which included members of the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government’s course, but initially only dealt with economic issues, including the euro and EU cooperation issues.
At the same time, the group opposed Germany’s “sponsorship” of weak EU economies, did not exclude the possibility of a return to the German mark and the country’s complete exit from the EU.
Against the background of the deepening immigration crisis, the political platform of ADG has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed a full-fledged party that occupied a niche of eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, ADG managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, receiving 94 deputy seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of "Alternatives for Germany" were given seats in the European Parliament.
