The Death Term of the Universe
The universe still exists for about 140 billion years, which is ten times the age of the observed world, equal to about 13.8 billion years.
The study by an international team of scientists is published in the library of electronic preprints arXiv.org and is intended for publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, reports the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
The researchers came to this conclusion by observing the HSC (Hyper Supprime-Cam) of the Subaru telescope over about ten million galaxies.
By tracking the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 percent of the mass energy of the observed world, the scientists, working within the standard cosmological model LCDM (L Cold Dark Matter), estimated the rate of expansion of the universe, which was slightly slower than previously thought.
In a press release from the Subaru Observatory, it was noted that the observations provided a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the universe, and the recording of data from the European Space Telescope Planck clarified the limitations imposed on the parameters of LCDM.
In July, scientists simulated the possible death of the universe.
Three years earlier, their colleagues had presented new arguments in favor of the fact that the observed world would cease to exist in 22 billion years as a result of the Big Bang.
