The main Macedonian opposition refused to vote in the referendum
In Macedonia on Sunday, September 30, a referendum is held on the issue of an intergovernmental treaty with Greece on the renaming of the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: “Do you support EU and NATO membership by accepting an agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Hellenic Republic?”
Nevertheless, the leader of the leading opposition party "Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity" (VMRO-DPMNE) Christian Mickosky said that he will not vote in the referendum.
According to party spokesman Naum Stoilkovsky, Mickosky decided to abstain from voting in order to express his disagreement with the treaty, which he considers "destructive".
According to the spokesperson, the current referendum resolves the question of renaming the country and nothing more, while the strategic goal of the party is to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago, Macedonian President Georgi Ivanov refused to participate in the referendum on September 30.
He explained that the name for the country he chose 27 years ago in a referendum on independence. the Macedonian leader considers the renaming of the country a negative factor.
"A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is being created," Ivanov said.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav Republic - the Republic of North Macedonia - was signed by the Foreign Ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a solemn ceremony on the shores of Lake Prespa, which crosses the border between the two countries.
The treaty should resolve a long-standing dispute over the country’s name, as well as Skopje’s path to NATO and the EU, TASS recalls.
